    "101": "bmp",
    "102": "dib",
    "103": "rle",
    "104": "Windows Bitmap",
    "105": "BMP is a standard format used by Windows to store device-independent and application-independent images. The number of bits per pixel for a given BMP file is specified in a file header and can range from 1 to 64. BMP files with 24 bits per pixel are common. BMP files are usually not compressed and therefore are not well suited for transfer across the Internet.",
    "106": "Bitmap Density",
    "107": "Specifies the resolution, in pixels-per-meter, of the target device for the bitmap. An application can use this value to select a bitmap from a resource group that best matches the characteristics of the current device",
    "108": "Bitmap channel order",
    "109": "Describes the order of color channels in a pixel of the image.",
    "1100": "cal",
    "1101": "mil",
    "1102": "rst",
    "1103": "cg4",
    "1104": "gp4",
    "1105": "CALS Type I",
    "1106": "CALS Image dimension compliance",
    "1107": "Byte (octet) boundaries. An encoding program exporting documents from a system for interchange shall produce documents with a pel path dimension and a line count dimension which is multiples of eight pels. If so specified in the contract document, decoding systems may be required to be able to import documents which have arbitrary dimensions from other, non-MIL-R-28002 compliant systems.",
    "1108": "The character string used by the source system to uniquely identify a document (e.g., a technical publication number, engineering drawing number, or database file set identifier)",
    "1109": "A character string used by the destination system to uniquely identify this document. This shall be the service or agency document number if one exists (e.g., a technical publication number or title, engineering drawing number, or database file set name)",
    "1110": "Id of a text file associated with this document.",
    "1111": "Figure Id",
    "1112": "File name of the source graphic",
    "1113": "A character string stating the highest security/sensitivity level or other restrictions on any file in the transfer unit.",
    "1114": "One, right-justified, four character string representing the numerical value of the raster image density expressed in pixels per inch. If more than one value is applicable to the data file, the ASCII character string \"MIXED\" shall be used. Permissible and default image density values are listed in MIL-R-28002.",
    "1115": "Notes shall consist of free form text consistent with the number of characters permitted for records in this file.",
    "1116": "A bitonal image format with a human readable header defined by the United States Government for the purpose of document storage and interchange.",
