    "7100": "JPEG File Interchange Format",
    "7101": "JPEG File Interchange Format (ISO/IEC IS 10918-1) is a minimal file format which enables JPEG bit streams to be exchanged between a wide variety of platforms and applications.",
    "7102": "JFIF Format Reader by Autodesk, Inc. All rights reserved. This software is based in part on the work of the Independent JPEG Group.",
    "7103": "jpg",
    "7112": "jpeg",
    "7104": "Density",
    "7105": "JFIF can encode separate X and Y density values as an integer number of pixels per unit.",
    "7106": "Comment",
    "7107": "JPEG can embed comments with the image file.",
    "7108": "Write Progressive JPEG",
    "7109": "Progressive JPEG rearranges the stored data into a series of scans of increasing quality.  In situations where a JPEG file is transmitted across a slow communications link, a decoder can generate a low-quality image very quickly from the first scan, then gradually improve the displayed quality as more scans are received.  ",
    "7110": "JPEG Compression (Quality)",
    "7111": "The compression method used in JPEG is \"lossy\". Color information is lost while trying to preserve visual fidelity of the image. The lower the \"quality\" the more color information may be lost and a greater compression may be achieved.",
    "17100": "JPEG2000",
    "17101": "JPEG2000 (ISO/IEC 15444-1:2004) uses wavelet based compression technology to compress images, resulting in very high quality results at very high compression rates.",
